1 (2) Whether the prisoner has completed a program of
2 general education, an industrial or vocational training program or
3 any other program for rehabilitation or treatment;
4 (f) Information on the background, personal history and
5 characteristics of the prisoner, including, without limitation,
6 whether, at the time the offense was committed, the prisoner was a
7 victim of domestic violence or sexual abuse;
8 (g) Any victim impact statement, other documents or testimony
9 submitted by the victim;
10 (h) Any evidence indicating that the sentence imposed was:
11 (1) Enhanced because the offender exercised his or her
12 constitutional right to a trial; or
13 (2) Inconsistent with the public policy set forth in NRS
14 176.0131 or any state laws, regulations or guidelines relating to
15 sentencing;
16 (i) Whether a stable plan for the release of the prisoner exists;
17 (j) Whether the prisoner has support available to him or her in
18 the community or from his or her family; and
19 (k) Any other evidence the Board deems relevant for purposes
20 of determining whether the release of the prisoner on parole
21 would benefit, or would not be dangerous to, society or the
22 prisoner.
23 8. The Board shall notify a prisoner of the Board’s decision
24 as to whether to grant second look parole in accordance with
25 subsection 11 of NRS 213.131.
26 9. At the time of the release of a prisoner on second look
27 parole, the Board shall prescribe the terms and conditions of the
28 second look parole.
29 10. A person who is granted second look parole pursuant to
30 this section is under the supervision of the Division. The Division
31 is responsible for supervising the person’s compliance with the
32 terms and conditions prescribed by the Board.
33 11. Except as otherwise provided in this subsection, the
34 Board shall not take any action on an application submitted
35 pursuant to subsection 2 if the prisoner to whom the application
36 pertains was previously denied second look parole and less than 24
37 months have elapsed since the most recent denial. The Board may
38 take action on such an application if a shorter period has been
39 prescribed by the Board or a request is made by the Director of the
40 Department.
41 12. The provisions of this section are not intended to replace
42 the provisions relating to the general eligibility and consideration
43 of parole provided in NRS 213.1099 and 213.1215.
44 13. The Board shall adopt any regulations necessary to carry
45 out the provisions of this section.
